"# Chapter 3: The Note

*\"We call it music, but we're really dealing with sound.\"*

In Chapter 1, you made a bare sine tone — a single frequency ringing for a duration. In Chapter 2, you learned how to bind names to values, how to build lists, how to make your own procedures with `lambda`, and how **macros** let you create new language forms. You even pulled a pitch from data and sounded it.

Now we give sound a **musical address**.

A note is not just a frequency and a duration. A note has a **pitch** (a name: `C4`, `A440`, `Eb5`), a **duration** (measured in beats, not milliseconds — because music keeps time), and a **velocity** (how hard you strike it, how loud it sounds). A note knows **where it belongs** in musical time.

This chapter introduces `(note pitch dur velocity)` — the verb that schedules a pitched sound at a musical moment. You'll also meet the **noises soundboard** (`sfx`) for percussion and effects, and the `beat` verb for rhythm patterns. By the end, you will play **Twinkle Twinkle Little Star** on piano — a complete melody, notated, sounded, and alive with the note-sprites you'll meet along the way.

This is the **end of the beginning**. After this chapter, you have the foundation to build anything musical in the runtime.

---

## 3.0 The four ways to make a sound in Motoi

Motoi has FOUR canonical ways to make a pitched sound, plus one drum verb. Every one of them is real and lives in CORE. Any other form you type — like a bare `(tone ...)` outside of Book of Music, or something you invent on the spot — is not a verb the runtime knows, and will not run.

Read this table once. It is the whole surface of pitched sound in Motoi.

| Form                                            | Pitch given as        | Duration in     | Example                                    |
|-------------------------------------------------|-----------------------|-----------------|--------------------------------------------|
| `(audio/play 'tone freq dur)`                   | frequency in Hz       | seconds         | `(audio/play 'tone 440 0.5)`               |
| `(audio/play 'note pitch-string dur)`           | pitch string          | seconds         | `(audio/play 'note \"C4\" 0.5)`              |
| `(note pitch-symbol dur velocity)`              | pitch symbol          | musical beats   | `(note 'C4 'quarter 64)`                   |
| `(note/strike pitch-string dur)`                | pitch string          | seconds         | `(note/strike \"C4\" 0.5)`                   |
| `(synth/play voice pitch-string dur)`           | pitch string          | seconds         | `(synth/play 'sine \"C4\" 0.5)`              |
| `(synth/kit name)`                              | (drum name)           | (kit default)   | `(synth/kit 'kick)`                        |

Middle C is `\"C4\"` (as a string), `'C4` (as a symbol), or `261.63` Hz. All five pitched forms above can play middle C:

```scheme
(audio/play 'tone 261.63 1.0)      ; frequency form
(audio/play 'note \"C4\" 1.0)        ; pitched form via audio/play
(note 'C4 'quarter 64)             ; musical form, one beat, medium velocity
(note/strike \"C4\" 1.0)             ; shorthand for the above
(synth/play 'sine \"C4\" 1.0)        ; with a voice tag
```

Every one of these plays a middle C. Which you pick is a matter of taste and what you already have on the page:

- Reach for **`audio/play`** when you're in Book of Scheme — kids know it from Chapter 1.
- Reach for **`note`** when you're writing music that thinks in beats and velocity, not seconds and default loudness.
- Reach for **`synth/play`** when you want to pick a voice (sine, square, triangle).

### The `(tone freq dur)` bare form — a Book-of-Music dialect

Because Book of Music was written to feel like a music textbook, it uses `(tone freq dur)` and `(beep)` as short, poetic forms at the start of Chapter 1. These are Book-of-Music-dialect aliases that expand to `(audio/play 'tone freq dur)` and a default beep under the hood. They are convenient when you're deep in the music chapters and want the shortest possible expression.

**Outside Book of Music — including when you're in the REPL, writing a cart, or composing anywhere else — reach for the canonical CORE forms:**

```scheme
;; Canonical:
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.5)

;; Book-of-Music dialect short form (only inside this book's context):
(tone 440 0.5)
```

If you see `(tone 440 0.5)` in a program and get an unbound-symbol error, the fix is one line: change it to `(audio/play 'tone 440 0.5)`.

### Common invented forms that DO NOT EXIST

Because sound has so many valid surfaces, the invented ones are hard to spot. Every one of these is WRONG and will error out:

```scheme
;; WRONG — play-tone is not a verb.
(play-tone 440 0.5)

;; WRONG — audio/tone is not the correct namespace.
(audio/tone 440 0.5)

;; WRONG — sound/play is not a verb.
(sound/play 440 0.5)

;; WRONG — note-play with a hyphen is not a verb.
(note-play \"C4\" 0.5)

;; WRONG — MIDI numbers are not accepted directly by these verbs.
(audio/play 'tone 60 0.5)       ; 60 as a frequency is 60 Hz, not middle C

;; WRONG — playnote (one word) is not a verb.
(playnote \"C4\" 0.5)
```

If your \"make a middle C\" program doesn't run, check that you spelled one of the five canonical forms exactly. `(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.5)` is the safest fallback — it is always in scope, always plays middle C, and never disagrees with the CORE registry.

---

## 1. The note verb — `(note pitch dur velocity)`

Here is the signature:

```scheme
(note pitch dur velocity)
```

- **`pitch`** — a symbol naming the pitch: `C4` (middle C), `A4` (440 Hz), `Eb5` (E-flat above middle C). Octave numbers follow scientific pitch notation: `C4` is middle C, `C5` is one octave higher, `C3` one octave lower.
- **`dur`** — a symbol naming the duration in musical time: `quarter`, `half`, `whole`, `eighth`, `sixteenth`, or `triplet` (triplet eighth). *[needs: GAP-1 for dotted/tuplets/32nd/64th]*.
- **`velocity`** — a number from `0` (silent) to `127` (loudest), borrowed from MIDI convention. Think of it as \"how hard you press the key.\" `64` is a comfortable medium, `96` is strong, `32` is soft.

When you call `(note ...)`, the sound engine schedules a pitched tone to play **at the current beat position** (initially beat 0, the downbeat). The note rings for its duration, then stops. The playhead advances by that duration, so the next note you schedule starts where the last one ended.

Let's play middle C for one beat, medium loud:

```scheme
(note 'C4 'quarter 64)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire this example → schedule one piano note at beat 0, dur=1 beat (quarter), vel=64 -->`

You hear a piano tone — a single `C4`, lasting one beat (at the default tempo of 120 BPM, that's 0.5 seconds), at medium velocity. The playhead is now at beat 1.

**Why not `(tone 261.63 0.5)`?** Because music doesn't think in Hertz and seconds. Music thinks in **pitches** (`C4`) and **beats** (`quarter`). A `note` lives in **musical time**, where changing the tempo scales every duration together. A `tone` is a raw sound — useful for synthesis experiments (Chapter 1), but not for music that breathes and keeps time.

---

## 2. Musical time — beats, not milliseconds

In Chapter 1, `(tone freq dur)` took `dur` in **seconds** — wall-clock time. A half-second tone is always half a second, no matter what.

But in music, durations are **relative to the tempo**. A quarter note at 120 BPM is 0.5 seconds. At 60 BPM, it's 1 second. At 240 BPM, it's 0.25 seconds. The **duration name** (`quarter`) stays the same; the **wall-clock duration** adapts.

The transport (the runtime's musical clock, introduced fully in Chapter 5) keeps the **current tempo** and the **current beat position**. When you schedule a note, the engine:

1. Looks up the current tempo (default 120 BPM).
2. Converts the duration name (`quarter`) to a beat count (1 beat).
3. Converts that beat count to seconds (at 120 BPM, 1 beat = 0.5 s).
4. Schedules the pitched tone to start at the current playhead position and ring for that wall-clock duration.
5. Advances the playhead by the beat count (1 beat), so the next note starts at beat 1.

You can set the tempo with `(transport/tempo bpm)`:

```scheme
(transport/tempo 60)
(note 'C4 'quarter 64)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire transport/tempo + note → schedule at 60 BPM, quarter = 1 second -->`

Now the same `quarter` note lasts **1 second** (because 60 BPM means one beat per second). The note name and duration name didn't change — only the tempo changed, and the wall-clock duration adapted.

For the rest of this chapter, we'll stay at **120 BPM** (the default). But know that every `note` you write will scale with the tempo you set.

---

## 3. A melody — three notes

Let's play three notes in sequence: C, E, G (a C major triad, arpeggiated):

```scheme
(note 'C4 'quarter 64)
(note 'E4 'quarter 64)
(note 'G4 'quarter 64)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire → schedule three piano notes at beats 0, 1, 2; total dur 3 beats -->`

You hear: **C** (beat 0), **E** (beat 1), **G** (beat 2). Each note lasts one beat; the playhead advances 1 beat after each, so they don't overlap — they play **in sequence**, not simultaneously. (Simultaneous notes — **polyphony** — come in Chapter 9.)

[VISUAL: Staff with treble clef, 4/4 time signature, three quarter notes: C4, E4, G4, each centered on beat 1, 2, 3. The note-sprites (quarter-note glyphs at 48×48 px) are drawn on the staff, each bopping gently in place at quarter-note tempo. When the corresponding note sounds, that glyph brightens / animates more visibly.]

`<!-- BUILD: render staff with three notes; schedule note-sprite bop + light on sound -->`

---

## 4. The note-sprites — notation comes alive

You just saw your first **living notation**. The quarter-note glyphs on the staff are not static images — they are **sprites**, the same way the runtime and the 16 blossoms are sprites. Each note-value (whole, half, quarter, eighth, sixteenth, and their rests) is a **48×48 px character** on the Curator-16 dot-matrix substrate, with a **16×16 px shrunk form** for dense staves.

Each note-sprite has a **personality** tied to its duration:

- **Whole notes** move slowly — they last the longest, so they drift / breathe at a languid pace.
- **Half notes** are a bit quicker.
- **Quarter notes** bop steadily (one bob per beat, if you're at 120 BPM).
- **Eighth notes** are perky, twice as fast.
- **Sixteenth notes** are jittery, four bobs per beat.

The motion tempo is proportional to `1 / duration` — shorter notes are faster, because they fit more moments into the same span of time.

**They bop.** Each note-sprite has a light **in-place bob** (a small vertical oscillation, using the substrate's in-place locomotion vocabulary — no arms, no leaving the staff position). A quarter note bobs at quarter-note tempo; an eighth bobs twice as fast.

**They light when sounding.** When you schedule a note and it plays, the corresponding note-sprite on the staff **brightens / animates more visibly** during the beat(s) that note is sounding. You **see** the sound happening.

**They are pressable.** Tap a note-sprite, and it **makes a sound** — a single note. **the runtime decides** which pitch and voice fit the moment (default is **piano**, middle register). So a note-sprite is a **playable object**: press it, hear it.

`<!-- BUILD: note-sprite press handler → schedule one note through the sound engine; default voice = piano; instrument overridable; when the runtime places note-sprites as decoration, she picks pitch+voice -->`

The note-sprites do **triple duty**:

1. **Notation** — rendering the book's (and the Music studio's) actual scores.
2. **Decoration** — the runtime scatters them as ornament when a song is playing, or as flourish on things she composes.
3. **Interactive elements** — the same primitives power the Music application, not just the book.

*\"You see them less, but they work with music.\"* They are **ambient participants** — subtle on the staff, not scene-stealing, but genuinely tied to the sounding music.

`<!-- BUILD: author note-value glyph sprites (whole, half, quarter, eighth, sixteenth, dotted variants, beams/flags) at 48×48 and 16×16 on Curator-16 dot substrate; one define-sprite per value + rest + clef + accidental -->`

`<!-- BUILD: give each note-value an idle motion signature (bop rate ∝ 1/duration) using in-place locomotion verbs; whole=slowest, sixteenth=fastest -->`

`<!-- BUILD: bind note-sprite animation to the sounding tape — a glyph bops/lights while its scheduled note is sounding at the current beat -->`

