### 34. A drum fill

A *fill* is a short burst of percussive hits at the end of a phrase. Here's a simple snare roll:

```scheme
;; Four snare hits in quick succession
(sfx \"snare\")
(sfx \"snare\")
(sfx \"snare\")
(sfx \"snare\")
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; triggers four snare hits -->

[VISUAL: percussion staff (single line, X noteheads) showing four snare hits as sixteenth notes, marked with accent symbols]

In a real drum part, you'd schedule these at precise beat positions. For now, they play in sequence. A fill punctuates the end of a phrase, signaling a transition.

---


### 35. A hi-hat ostinato with kicks

An *ostinato* is a repeated pattern. A simple rock beat: hi-hat on every eighth note, kick on beats 1 and 3:

```scheme
;; Simulate two bars of hi-hat eighths with kick on 1 and 3 of each bar
(define (hat-kick-pattern)
  (sfx \"kick\")
  (sfx \"hat\")
  (sfx \"hat\")
  (sfx \"hat\")
  (sfx \"kick\")
  (sfx \"hat\")
  (sfx \"hat\")
  (sfx \"hat\"))

(hat-kick-pattern)
(hat-kick-pattern)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; triggers 16 sfx calls in a kick/hat pattern -->

[VISUAL: percussion grid showing two rows (kick, hat), eight columns (beats), with kick on columns 0 and 4, hi-hat on all eight columns]

This is a *drum loop*. The pattern repeats. In Ch5 we'll learn to schedule it properly on the transport; for now it's a *sequential approximation*.

---


### 36. A clap accent on the backbeat

In many genres, a handclap (or snare) lands on beats 2 and 4 (the *backbeat*):

```scheme
;; Four-beat pattern: kick on 1 and 3, clap on 2 and 4
(sfx \"kick\")
(sfx \"clap\")
(sfx \"kick\")
(sfx \"clap\")
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; triggers four sfx calls in kick-clap-kick-clap order -->

[VISUAL: percussion grid, four beats, kick on 1 and 3, clap on 2 and 4]

The backbeat clap is the *signature* of rock, funk, and pop. It's what makes you want to clap along on 2 and 4.

---


### 37. A polyrhythmic drum pattern (simulated)

*Polyrhythm* means multiple rhythms at once. Here's a kick playing every three eighth notes, and a hi-hat playing every four eighth notes, over a 12-beat cycle:

```scheme
;; Kick on beats 0, 3, 6, 9 (every 3 eighths)
;; Hat on beats 0, 4, 8 (every 4 eighths)
;; We simulate by listing all 12 eighths and firing the appropriate sfx
(define pattern-12
  '((kick hat)
    ()
    ()
    (kick)
    (hat)
    ()
    (kick)
    ()
    (kick hat)
    ()
    ()
    (kick)))

(define (play-poly-pattern pattern)
  (for-each
    (lambda (step)
      (for-each
        (lambda (s)
          (sfx (symbol->string s)))
        step))
    pattern))

(play-poly-pattern pattern-12)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; triggers kick and hat sfx according to the 12-step polyrhythmic grid -->

[VISUAL: 12-column grid, two rows (kick in 3s, hat in 4s), showing the phasing pattern where they coincide on beats 0 and 8]

This is a *3-against-4* polyrhythm (or the LCM, 12 eighth notes). Chapter 10 will explore polyrhythm in depth; this is a preview.

---


### 38. A shaker texture layer

A *shaker* is a continuous rattling sound. We can simulate a steady shaker layer by triggering it on every sixteenth note:

```scheme
;; 16 shaker hits (one bar of sixteenths at common tempo)
(define (shaker-layer n)
  (when (> n 0)
    (sfx \"shaker\")
    (shaker-layer (- n 1))))

(shaker-layer 16)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; triggers 16 shaker sfx calls -->

[VISUAL: percussion staff showing 16 sixteenth notes all marked as shaker, beamed in groups of four]

The shaker provides a *textural layer* — constant, quiet, in the background. It doesn't carry melody or harmony, but it adds *motion*.

---


### 39. A kick-snare-hat loop (the \"boom-bap\")

The classic hip-hop drum pattern: kick on 1 and 3, snare on 2 and 4, closed hi-hat on every eighth:

```scheme
;; Eight-step loop (two bars of quarter notes, hi-hat as eighths)
(define boom-bap
  '((kick hat)
    (hat)
    (snare hat)
    (hat)
    (kick hat)
    (hat)
    (snare hat)
    (hat)))

(define (play-boom-bap pattern)
  (for-each
    (lambda (step)
      (for-each
        (lambda (sound)
          (sfx (symbol->string sound)))
        step))
    pattern))

(play-boom-bap boom-bap)
(play-boom-bap boom-bap)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; plays the eight-step boom-bap pattern twice -->

[VISUAL: percussion grid showing two bars, kick row with hits on beats 1 and 3 of each bar, snare row on 2 and 4, hi-hat row on every eighth note]

This is the *boom-bap* — the foundation of 90s hip-hop. The pattern is data; we can swap out sounds (replace snare with clap, replace hat with shaker) and create variants.

---


### 40. A closing Twinkle with bass and drums

Pull everything together: the Twinkle melody, a simple bass line, and a kick-hat pattern:

```scheme
;; Twinkle melody (first phrase): C C G G A A G
(define melody '(60 60 67 67 69 69 67))

;; Bass line (one note per melody note, mostly root/fifth)
(define bass '(36 36 43 43 45 45 43))

;; Drum pattern: kick on each beat, hat on off-beats (simulated by playing after each melody note)

(define (play-arrangement melody bass)
  (for-each
    (lambda (m b)
      (note/strike b 'quarter 75)       ; bass
      (note/strike m 'quarter 80)       ; melody
      (sfx \"kick\"))                     ; kick on the beat
    melody bass))

(play-arrangement melody bass)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete standalone program; plays seven melody+bass+kick events -->

[VISUAL: a three-staff score — top staff treble clef with melody, middle staff bass clef with bass line, bottom staff percussion with kick hits aligned to each beat]

This is a *multi-timbral arrangement*: melody (piano), bass (piano low register), drums (sfx). Each layer plays its own data; the `play-arrangement` function synchronizes them. This is the seed of Chapter 14's full orchestration.

